<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Twilight Denial<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.52)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9034'>David "Turambar" F</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9034&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 27, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> (from the Free Peoples perspective)<br>
<br>
The Twilight pool often holds the key to winning games, and embodies the element of risk. Putting down that Gandalf may just give your opponent the gear he needs to slide a Witch-King down, whereas not putting him down might cause a weak fellowship to succumb to smaller minions. Generally, in this game, you want to be trying to play what you want, yet limit the things your opponent can play, and that can only be limiting the twilight pool.<br>
<br>
The factors that can manipulate twilight:<br>
1) Sites<br>
2) Fellowship<br>
3) Cultures/Cards<br>
<br>
SITES:<br>
<br>
All sites except Site 1 (because that would be stupid) and Site 3 (because Elrond is a coward) have a twilight number, which varies, and adds to the twilight pool whenever you move. Therefore, passing all your fellowship phases will not spare you from any shadow forces. When assembling your adventure deck, know well if you plan to stay ahead or behind your opponent, and if you choose the former, always squeeze in Thror&#39;s Map or Pathfinder. Your opponent&#39;s sites will always benefit him (unless he&#39;s stupid) and this often comes in the form of twilight. Shores of Nen Hithoel (site 8) is a popular site due to its high twilight number. Ford of Bruinen and other early Nazgul-benefit cards are also dangerous as they &#39;override&#39; twilight in many cases. Existence of Thror&#39;s Map and Pathfinder can eliminate or reduce these threats.<br>
<br>
The only site that directly affects twilight is Council Courtyard (site 3), which allows you to remove 2 twilight from the pool when you leave. Highly recommend this if you build your deck around twilight denial. If you rest at the sanctuary, on your fellowship turn, you are realistically playing your first one or two free peoples cards (depending on the twilight cost) free, and with Site 4&#39;s relatively low twilight number, you will be giving any shadow player but Moria a headache. Speeding past the sanctuary can also be considered if you have little to no wounds, and Council Courtyard can make the journey much less perilous. 2 Twilight to Isengard and Sauron forces upon them the roaming penalty, allowing definitely one less minion to arrive. Moria, if having a bad hand, cannot possibly function, and Nazgul, the highest twilight-intensive culture, will have to wait for the Bridge of Khazad-dum.<br>
<br>
<br>
FELLOWSHIP:<br>
<br>
The ratio of the size of the fellowship to the size of the twilight pool, which is itself is relative to the number of minions and shadow cards, is directly proportional. Logical, considering a larger fellowship would attract more readily the attention of the shadows. Not only will you have to add 1 twilight for every companion when you move, you also have to pay the cost for them when you play them. Thus can it be concluded that the first step to a deck that stinges on twilight is to use a small fellowship. If you go on about the disadvantages of a small fellowship (Moria swarm, Sauron conditions etc), then forget it. There is no way to build a large fellowship which will give little twilight. A fellowship of 4-5 is the bare maximum of its size (and if No Stranger to the Shadows and A Talent For Being Seen are included, so much the better). Any greater and prepare to fight a war every turn.<br>
<br>
The only factors that affect this ratio, notwithstanding Moria and shadow twilight bonuses, are cards like No Stranger to the Shadows, A Talent For Not Being Seen (and in the next set, Bill the Pony). These cards have the feature of letting the bearer travel for free (except when moving to Site 3), and are staples in a Twilight Denial deck. Think of Arwen, Aragorn and Boromir rare all being No Stranger and Frodo and Sam sharing A Talent For Not Being Seen. With Bill the Pony (which is roughly the same text as No Stranger but bearer must be a hobbit and it must be discarded at an underground site) coming, The above example can actually allow the fellowship to travel free, the only addition to the twilight pool being the site&#39;s twilight number, and with the greatest twilight number at 9 and the average at around 5 or 6, added with cautious twilight regulation with the cards you play, it can seriously limit the resistance you will meet along the adventure path.<br>
<br>
<br>
CARDS:<br>
<br>
Time to go through every free peoples card that can manipulate twilight pool to a lower number.<br>
<br>
Dwarves:<br>
Durin&#39;s folk does not bother with stealth and courtesy. They charge at you and bear you down. Nothing here for twilight denial and shadow prevention.<br>
<br>
Elves:<br>
<br>
 -Galadriel, Lady of Light (exert to play an Elf for free)<br>
If your deck consists of a large dose of elves, look no further than her. Even if you are not using the Mirror (and you should if you use Galadriel), she can often prevent that one strong minion from coming out. The twilight cost of elves can range from 1 (Lorien Elf), to the average of 2 (Arwen, Legolas, Haldir, Celeborn, Rumil, Orophin) to 4 (Elrond). Drawing and playing Galadriel early has the effect of taking away all the twilight costs of the elves you will play later. Sure, it may not affect them when they move, but it makes the decision of playing that Elf (should I play Elrond and risk a Lurtz?) much easier. Take into account that most elves are allies (or in your starting fellowship). Galadriel makes them 0 cost, not giving any twilight to your opponent.<br>
<br>
 -Silinde bearing the text of Council Courtyard<br>
That&#39;s not legal, folks. Council Courtyard&#39;s text specifies that the -2 happens only when you leave Council Courtyard, and there is really only one time when you can do that.<br>
<br>
Gandalf:<br>
Gandalf is not afraid of the shadows and can thus rack up huge amounts of twilight in a single turn.<br>
<br>
 -The Nine Walkers<br>
Gandalf decks are often varied in races to maximise the use of Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk. This card can make pulling the companions out much cheaper, with all elves and dwarves coming out for free and men coming out for 1 or 2. The only problem here is that you might actually draw it AFTER you play the companions. Worth a try, though not recommended.<br>
<br>
 -Glamdring<br>
Effective to use when you are flooding the twilight pool, and plus it could actually be free to get into play (not counting the exertion) in some instances if your opponent plays Orcs. With Strength of Spirit, you can exert multiple times to actually reduce the twilight pool to nothing, and if he does not, it is useful to check his hand to see if it will be wise to keep those cards in your hand and deny him the twilight needed for his cards if he has many effective cards to play.<br>
<br>
 -Gandalf, the Grey Wizard<br>
With the Strength of Spirits you are bound to run with Gandalf and the possibility to heal the wound immediately if you play Pippin rare, this card is passable. It can play Pippin rare, Legolas uncommon, Frodo rare (try it), Gimli rare for free and Aragorn rare for 2. The catch is that Gandalf the Grey is not effective as a whole, with a measly strength of 7, while Gandalf FotS can boast of a maximum of 10<br>
<br>
Gondor:<br>
<br>
-An Able Guide<br>
Aiding double-moves, An Able Guide is commonly regarded as a weak rare, as it can only be used during the regroup phase, and by then, there is usually no twilight in the pool or none to make a difference.<br>
<br>
-No Stranger to the Shadows<br>
See Fellowship section<br>
<br>
Shire:<br>
<br>
-The Gaffer&#39;s Pipe<br>
A consistent way of removing twilight when it rises too much, but remember it is a pipe, and pipes are very card-intensive for *more* pipes, pipeweed and perhaps Gandalf&#39;s Cart. Not too bad, just remember to use Bilbo to recycle the Pipeweed.<br>
<br>
-Sting<br>
See Glamdring<br>
<br>
-A Talent For Not Being Seen<br>
See Fellowship section<br>
<br>
<br>
Against the shadows:<br>
<br>
Moria:<br>
Twilight denial is rather ineffective. With just 2 or 3 in the pool, they can crazily add to it with Goblin Runners and multiple Goblin Armories and then slap down the big minions. With the small fellowship you are generally bringing along, this can hurt a lot.<br>
<br>
Isengard:<br>
Effective. Isengard relies on twilight, but in the sense that they may need more to boost a Slayer, more for Uruk-Hai Rampage, or perhaps even Alive and Unspoiled. Twilight denial can limit or prevent these prospects of stronger and fiercer minions or discarding. The Uruk-Hai are also very hard to get out before Site 5 with proper twilight control, and after that, every Uruk-Hai minion which was prevented from entering play is often a companion saved from death.<br>
<br>
Ringwraith:<br>
Effective. The Nazgul are largely the most expensive minions around and proper twilight control can limit yourself to facing 1 a turn, and stopping an annoying card like Beauty is Fading. There is nothing you can do with Ford of Bruinen and Morgul Gates however.<br>
<br>
Sauron:<br>
Their roaming till site 6 makes them unable to touch you before then with twilight denial. The road from there will be harder, however, as Sauron minions are effective for their cost, most notably the direct-damage ones, and the Orc Bowmen who have been stocked up can rain down. By then, however, it is usually too late for your opponent to make a difference. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3202&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
